709
01:11:57,918 --> 01:12:00,338
Isn't that a cute story, Jess?

710
01:12:09,819 --> 01:12:12,568
Give me some more conversations, Bob.

711
01:12:17,434 --> 01:12:22,388
I got one. This one's about as crackerjack...
It's the one about your...

712
01:12:22,555 --> 01:12:24,376
Let Bob tell it.

713
01:12:25,690 --> 01:12:27,413
All right.

714
01:12:33,689 --> 01:12:35,597
I don't even know
what you're talking about.

715
01:12:35,768 --> 01:12:39,598
About how you and Jesse
have so much in common.

716
01:12:42,521 --> 01:12:44,113
Go on, Bob.

717
01:12:44,280 --> 01:12:46,169
Yeah, come on, Bob.

718
01:12:46,872 --> 01:12:49,043
Tell us a story.

719
01:12:50,905 --> 01:12:55,312
- Nope. No.
- Come on, entertain Jesse. He's here.

720
01:13:01,973 --> 01:13:03,437
Come on.

721
01:13:10,038 --> 01:13:13,780
Well, if you'll pardon my saying so,
I guess...

722
01:13:13,942 --> 01:13:17,836
...it is interesting the many ways
you and I overlap and whatnot.

723
01:13:19,091 --> 01:13:21,742
I mean, you begin with our daddies.

724
01:13:21,909 --> 01:13:24,755
Your daddy was a pastor
at the New Hope Baptist Church...

725
01:13:24,917 --> 01:13:29,456
...and my daddy was a pastor
at the church in Excelsior Springs.

726
01:13:30,836 --> 01:13:34,992
You're the youngest of three James boys,
and I'm the youngest of five Ford boys.

727
01:13:36,723 --> 01:13:39,275
Between Charley and me,
there's another brother, Wilbur...

728
01:13:39,442 --> 01:13:41,385
...with six letters in his name.

729
01:13:41,715 --> 01:13:47,081
And between Frank and you, is another
brother Robert, also with six letters.

730
01:13:47,282 --> 01:13:50,860
And my Christian name
is Robert, of course.

731
01:13:52,145 --> 01:13:54,218
You have blue eyes, I have blue eyes.

732
01:13:54,387 --> 01:13:58,215
You're 5'8"tall, I'm 5'8" tall.

733
01:14:02,769 --> 01:14:07,919
Me, I must have had a list as long as
your nightshirt when I was 12, but...

734
01:14:08,082 --> 01:14:11,375
...I seem to have lost some curiosities
over the years.

735
01:14:28,873 --> 01:14:30,982
Ain't he something?

736
01:14:43,050 --> 01:14:47,076
Did I ever tell you the story about
that scalawag, George Shepherd?

737
01:14:47,370 --> 01:14:49,194
Shepherd's one of
Quantrill's lieutenants.

738
01:14:49,354 --> 01:14:51,939
He give me a story much like Bob's
what bring him to mind.

739
01:14:52,392 --> 01:14:54,814
Going on about how much
we had in common, and so on...

740
01:14:54,985 --> 01:14:57,407
...so he could get in the gang.

741
01:14:57,577 --> 01:15:00,576
How could I have known
he had a grudge against me?

742
01:15:00,744 --> 01:15:05,054
How could I have known
he was lying to get on my good side?

743
01:15:05,224 --> 01:15:10,014
I said, "George, come on aboard.
Glad to have you."

744
01:15:10,183 --> 01:15:14,786
George thought he was smart,
except he wasn't.

745
01:15:15,686 --> 01:15:18,686
One morning, George rides into camp...

746
01:15:18,855 --> 01:15:20,959
...and about 20 guns open up on him.

747
01:15:24,613 --> 01:15:28,891
See, old George, he only had one eye. You
gotta have two eyes, you wanna get Jesse.

748
01:15:33,542 --> 01:15:36,541
You ought not think of me
like you do George Shepherd.

749
01:15:37,829 --> 01:15:39,967
You brought him to mind.

750
01:15:40,870 --> 01:15:43,073
Well, it's not very flattering.

751
01:15:48,805 --> 01:15:51,488
Sure is good eating, Martha.

752
01:15:52,323 --> 01:15:54,462
Well, I'm so glad you enjoyed it.

753
01:15:54,628 --> 01:15:56,699
How come George
had a grudge against you?

754
01:16:01,410 --> 01:16:05,339
I said, how come George
had a grudge against you?

755
01:16:10,817 --> 01:16:15,357
Well, you see, George had a nephew
he wanted me to protect during the war.

756
01:16:15,522 --> 01:16:17,662
This nephew had 5000 dollars on him.

757
01:16:17,826 --> 01:16:22,232
It just so happens he winds up killed
and someone swipes that money.

758
01:16:22,402 --> 01:16:26,110
And when George is in prison,
someone whispers to him:

759
01:16:26,272 --> 01:16:29,850
"It was Jesse James
slit the boy's throat."

760
01:16:34,399 --> 01:16:36,767
It was just mean gossip, was it?

761
01:16:38,495 --> 01:16:41,660
Bob's the expert. Let's put it to him.

762
01:16:46,526 --> 01:16:48,828
Oh, dear, I made him cranky.

763
01:16:48,990 --> 01:16:52,633
I'm not cranky. I just been
through this before is all.

764
01:16:52,797 --> 01:16:55,832
Most people get around on making fun
of me. They don't ever let up.

765
01:16:55,998 --> 01:16:57,974
Someone's getting awful fresh over there.

766
01:16:58,142 --> 01:17:00,728
Woman, shut your face for once.

767
01:17:07,451 --> 01:17:09,690
Don't want you to skip off
to your room and pout...

768
01:17:09,852 --> 01:17:12,273
...without knowing why I come by
for this visit.

769
01:17:13,053 --> 01:17:15,191
Why? So you could
tell us how sorry you are...

770
01:17:15,356 --> 01:17:17,810
...you had to slap our cousin Albert around?

771
01:17:30,873 --> 01:17:32,630
I come by...

772
01:17:32,794 --> 01:17:36,056
...to ask if one of you two Fords...

773
01:17:36,249 --> 01:17:39,480
...would care to ride with me
in a journey or two.

774
01:17:39,865 --> 01:17:43,093
I guess we both agree
it ought to be Charley.

775
01:17:43,256 --> 01:17:45,941
You've been acting sort of testy.

776
01:18:15,767 --> 01:18:17,904
Have you seen Wood Hite lately?

777
01:18:18,389 --> 01:18:21,773
No. Not at all.

778
01:18:29,430 --> 01:18:31,983
I swear that stew
had some squirrel meat in it.

779
01:18:32,149 --> 01:18:34,735
- Still arguing with you, is it?
- Yeah.

780
01:18:35,478 --> 01:18:37,333
- You're Charles Ford?
- Yes, ma'am.

781
01:18:37,494 --> 01:18:39,467
You've seen me once or twice before.

782
01:18:40,757 --> 01:18:42,611
I got a letter from George Hite.

783
01:18:43,220 --> 01:18:46,002
He hasn't seen hide nor hair of him.

784
01:18:47,443 --> 01:18:49,549
And you say you haven't seen Wood?

785
01:18:50,260 --> 01:18:53,293
No, l... I can't imagine where he could be.

786
01:19:19,569 --> 01:19:20,553
Yeah?

787
01:19:21,681 --> 01:19:23,753
You finished with your sleeping?

788
01:19:25,199 --> 01:19:27,620
I could use a couple more hours
if it's no trouble.

789
01:19:38,799 --> 01:19:40,293
Yeah.

790
01:19:43,791 --> 01:19:48,046
I been holding a discussion with myself
over if I ought to tell you this or no.

791
01:19:48,206 --> 01:19:50,758
My good side won out and...

792
01:19:51,919 --> 01:19:54,700
Well, I wanna make a clean breast
of things.

793
01:19:55,758 --> 01:19:59,752
Yeah, my mind's a little cobwebby
is the only drawback.

794
01:19:59,916 --> 01:20:04,522
I could use a little...
A little more sleep.

795
01:20:06,956 --> 01:20:08,900
You know I went to Kentucky?

796
01:20:09,837 --> 01:20:11,211
Yeah.

797
01:20:11,883 --> 01:20:14,217
I come back through Saline County and...

798
01:20:15,564 --> 01:20:17,352
...I think to myself:

799
01:20:17,868 --> 01:20:22,439
"Why not stop by and see Ed Miller?"

800
01:20:24,524 --> 01:20:26,181
So I do.

801
01:20:29,867 --> 01:20:33,063
Well, things are not to my satisfaction.

802
01:20:35,114 --> 01:20:37,763
Ed's got himself all worked up
over something.

803
01:20:39,242 --> 01:20:42,372
I can see that he's lying like a rug.

804
01:20:45,577 --> 01:20:48,545
So I say to myself, "Enough's enough."

805
01:20:49,033 --> 01:20:51,716
And I say to Ed, "Come on, Ed.

806
01:20:52,617 --> 01:20:54,853
Let's go for a ride."

807
01:20:56,583 --> 01:20:59,365
You understand what I'm saying?

808
01:21:00,552 --> 01:21:03,399
Going for a ride is like...

809
01:21:04,421 --> 01:21:07,422
Going for a ride
is like giving him what-for?

810
01:21:09,318 --> 01:21:10,977
Exactly.

811
01:21:15,273 --> 01:21:16,678
So...

812
01:21:19,270 --> 01:21:21,059
...Ed and Jesse...

813
01:21:23,365 --> 01:21:25,535
...they argue on the road.

814
01:21:29,797 --> 01:21:32,033
Did you ever count the stars?

815
01:21:35,364 --> 01:21:39,139
I can't ever get the same number.
They keep changing on me.

816
01:21:40,932 --> 01:21:43,833
I don't even know what a star is exactly.

817
01:21:46,434 --> 01:21:48,541
Well, your body knows.

818
01:21:49,410 --> 01:21:51,778
It's your mind that forgot.

819
01:22:01,154 --> 01:22:04,088
You go on ahead, partner.
I'll catch up with you.

820
01:22:42,654 --> 01:22:44,410
It's okay.

821
01:23:06,301 --> 01:23:09,617
It's okay, sweetheart. It's okay.

822
01:23:12,507 --> 01:23:14,874
And when push came to shove...

823
01:23:21,465 --> 01:23:23,767
...Jesse shot and killed him.

824
01:23:26,970 --> 01:23:28,759
Jesse did.

825
01:23:31,130 --> 01:23:32,789
You got it.

826
01:23:34,746 --> 01:23:36,056
You...

827
01:23:51,958 --> 01:23:53,846
So, you see, your...

828
01:23:54,038 --> 01:23:56,407
Your cousin, he got off easy.

829
01:23:56,567 --> 01:23:58,095
I was just playing with Albert.

830
01:23:59,543 --> 01:24:03,056
Yeah, I made him squeal
once or twice myself.

831
01:24:03,350 --> 01:24:06,285
I'm just not as thorough as you are.

832
01:24:17,109 --> 01:24:20,011
You got a tale to swap with me now?

833
01:24:28,437 --> 01:24:30,737
I don't get your meaning.

834
01:24:32,725 --> 01:24:37,808
Seems to me, if you have something
to confess in exchange...

835
01:24:37,972 --> 01:24:40,044
...it'd only be right...

836
01:24:40,914 --> 01:24:44,110
...that you'd spit it out now.

837
01:24:55,442 --> 01:24:57,482
I can't think of a single thing.

838
01:25:00,275 --> 01:25:02,923
About Wood Hite, for example.

839
01:25:03,088 --> 01:25:07,725
I'm not gonna... I been saying over and
over I can't figure out where he's gone.

840
01:25:07,888 --> 01:25:10,822
Now, I'm not gonna change my story
just to have something to spit.

841
01:25:10,992 --> 01:25:13,578
- Why was your brother so agitated?
- Which?

842
01:25:14,513 --> 01:25:15,559
Bob.

843
01:25:16,878 --> 01:25:19,748
That's just his way. He's antsy.

844
01:25:20,496 --> 01:25:21,869
You know?

845
01:25:37,388 --> 01:25:39,876
You go on back to sleep now.

846
01:25:41,453 --> 01:25:44,453
You got me agitated now, you see?

847
01:25:50,606 --> 01:25:54,631
Yeah, just ain't no peace
when old Jesse's around.

848
01:25:55,147 --> 01:25:58,016
You ought to pity my poor wife.

849
01:26:00,587 --> 01:26:02,658
Ed Miller was a good friend of mine.

850
01:26:02,825 --> 01:26:06,123
He introduced me to you
at that one poker game.

851
01:26:06,828 --> 01:26:10,690
I'm a little angry with you, if you
wanna know the God's honest truth.

852
01:26:13,066 --> 01:26:15,454
You ought to pity me too.

853
01:26:59,143 --> 01:27:02,916
As proof of his confederacy with
the James Gang, Bob told the authorities...

854
01:27:03,174 --> 01:27:06,522
...that Dick Liddil was sleeping over
at the rented farmhouse...

855
01:27:06,694 --> 01:27:09,410
...while his ruined leg mended.

856
01:27:14,212 --> 01:27:17,890
And then, created a map
of the Harbison property...

857
01:27:19,013 --> 01:27:24,030
...leaving out the creek where
Wood Hite's remains now moldered.

858
01:27:24,771 --> 01:27:26,875
Right, you boys are cornered!

859
01:27:27,043 --> 01:27:31,385
Come on out peaceably
and nobody'll get shot up!

860
01:27:36,323 --> 01:27:37,305
Don't shoot!

861
01:27:41,730 --> 01:27:43,638
Come on out and show yourself!

862
01:27:58,079 --> 01:27:59,542
Hello.

863
01:27:59,872 --> 01:28:01,433
We got him.

864
01:28:01,824 --> 01:28:03,766
Give me that Colt, son.

865
01:28:08,512 --> 01:28:10,966
- All right.
- Andrew James Liddil...

866
01:28:11,135 --> 01:28:14,005
...I have a warrant here
for your arrest...

867
01:28:14,174 --> 01:28:18,365
Snowstorms would move over Missouri
that Sunday, February 19th...

868
01:28:18,525 --> 01:28:21,395
...shutting down commerce
for more than two days.

869
01:28:22,973 --> 01:28:25,591
- Go, go, go.
- Are the papers here?

870
01:28:25,758 --> 01:28:29,237
- He wanted to know if the papers are here.
- I don't care what he wants.

871
01:28:29,406 --> 01:28:31,196
Yet this wouldn't prevent Robert Ford...

872
01:28:31,358 --> 01:28:33,660
...from presenting himself
to Governor Crittenden...

873
01:28:33,822 --> 01:28:36,787
...at the Craig Rifles Ball on Wednesday.

874
01:28:36,956 --> 01:28:40,373
I deem it a great privilege
on this glorious occasion...

875
01:28:40,539 --> 01:28:42,450
...to recognize publicly...

876
01:28:42,620 --> 01:28:45,173
...the intelligent and effective assistance...

877
01:28:45,339 --> 01:28:49,943
...that Captain Henry Craig has rendered
the state of Missouri and myself...

878
01:28:50,107 --> 01:28:53,422
...in our joint quest
to rid Jackson County...

879
01:28:53,820 --> 01:28:55,706
...of the James band.

880
01:28:55,867 --> 01:28:58,387
The task that Captain Craig
has assumed...

881
01:28:58,555 --> 01:29:02,515
...will require fearless courage,
extraordinary vigilance...

882
01:29:02,681 --> 01:29:05,496
...and an unerring selection
of instrumentalities.

883
01:29:06,617 --> 01:29:11,090
Well, I've gotten the signal from my wife
that enough is enough.

884
01:29:11,257 --> 01:29:13,527
However, before I sit...

885
01:29:13,690 --> 01:29:16,688
...I would like to ask you
to join me in a toast...

886
01:29:17,114 --> 01:29:20,658
...to a great son
of the state of Missouri...

887
01:29:20,824 --> 01:29:24,500
...my friend, Henry Craig.
- Here, here.

888
01:29:36,663 --> 01:29:38,224
Yes.

889
01:29:39,159 --> 01:29:40,915
Just let my attorney know.

890
01:29:48,245 --> 01:29:51,376
Who is that? Who is it?

891
01:29:51,701 --> 01:29:53,197
Get out of the way now.

892
01:30:02,771 --> 01:30:06,700
You know, you're more goddamn trouble
than you're worth, Bob.

893
01:30:06,867 --> 01:30:08,492
I was just gonna say hello.

894
01:30:08,660 --> 01:30:11,758
No, you weren't gonna do that, Bob.
That's not why you're down here.

895
01:30:11,923 --> 01:30:16,974
You think it's your goddamn coming-out.
You think you're the belle of the ball.

896
01:30:17,138 --> 01:30:21,198
Now you get upstairs and try to keep your
identity secret, you silly little bastard.

897
01:30:21,363 --> 01:30:24,112
The governor'll see you in good time.
Take him up, boys.

898
01:30:29,393 --> 01:30:31,434
Bob would later be cross-examined
repeatedly...

899
01:30:31,601 --> 01:30:35,628
...about the exact nature of the deal
he had made with the authorities.

900
01:30:35,792 --> 01:30:38,608
And he was never consistent
in his recollections.

901
01:30:42,609 --> 01:30:46,667
My wife's asleep in the other room,
so let's speak as quietly as we can.

902
01:30:47,312 --> 01:30:49,451
So you're Dick Little.

903
01:30:51,249 --> 01:30:52,709
Liddil.

904
01:30:53,423 --> 01:30:55,278
I beg your pardon?

905
01:30:55,566 --> 01:30:57,092
I spell it with two D's.

906
01:30:57,262 --> 01:30:59,532
He's given us a full confession, governor.

907
01:30:59,695 --> 01:31:01,701
Newspapers haven't caught onto it yet.

908
01:31:01,870 --> 01:31:05,254
And you've guaranteed him
a conditional pardon...

909
01:31:05,421 --> 01:31:09,133
...and amnesty for all the robberies
he's committed.

910
01:31:10,700 --> 01:31:11,881
You Robert Ford?

911
01:31:15,246 --> 01:31:16,490
How old are you?

912
01:31:18,477 --> 01:31:19,851
Twenty.

913
01:31:20,142 --> 01:31:22,562
You surrender to Sheriff Timberlake
as well?

914
01:31:22,734 --> 01:31:26,475
No, no, governor. That's his brother,
Charley Ford, he's in the James Gang.

915
01:31:26,636 --> 01:31:29,254
But little Bob here,
we got nothing on Bob.

916
01:31:29,420 --> 01:31:31,875
He's just acting in capacity as a...

917
01:31:33,996 --> 01:31:36,070
...private detective.

918
01:31:37,196 --> 01:31:39,137
Jesse James sent me a telegram
last month...

919
01:31:39,307 --> 01:31:42,340
...saying he'd kill me
if he had to wreck a train to do it.

920
01:31:42,506 --> 01:31:45,026
He said once I got in his hands,
he'd cut my heart out...

921
01:31:45,194 --> 01:31:47,583
...and eat it in strips like it was bacon.

922
01:31:47,755 --> 01:31:49,609
I'll wreck his train first.

923
01:31:56,874 --> 01:32:00,868
I'm sorry, Your Excellency.
I was thinking about something else.

924
01:32:01,035 --> 01:32:03,269
Jesse James is nothing more
than a public outlaw...

925
01:32:03,432 --> 01:32:06,116
...who made his reputation
by stealing whatever he wanted...

926
01:32:06,280 --> 01:32:08,419
...killing whoever got in his way.

927
01:32:08,584 --> 01:32:12,032
You'll hear some fools say he's getting back
at Republicans and Union men...

928
01:32:12,200 --> 01:32:14,850
...for the wrongs his family suffered
during the war.

929
01:32:15,016 --> 01:32:19,555
But his victims have scarcely been selected
with reference to their political views.

930
01:32:20,038 --> 01:32:22,625
I'm saying his sins will soon find him out.

931
01:32:22,791 --> 01:32:25,344
I'm saying his cup of iniquity is full.

932
01:32:25,510 --> 01:32:28,097
I'm saying Jesse James
is a desperate case...

933
01:32:28,391 --> 01:32:31,174
...and may require a desperate remedy.

934
01:32:34,376 --> 01:32:37,342
Y'all got the right man for the job.

935
01:32:53,028 --> 01:32:55,199
Come on. Come on, now.

936
01:32:55,747 --> 01:32:57,310
Come on, now.

937
01:33:39,871 --> 01:33:42,327
Have you ever considered suicide?

938
01:33:44,288 --> 01:33:49,405
I can't say that I have. There's always
something else I wanted to do.

939
01:33:50,431 --> 01:33:56,061
Or my predicaments changed,
or I saw my hardships from a different slant.

940
01:33:56,223 --> 01:34:00,444
You know all what can happen.
It never seemed respectable.

941
01:34:06,942 --> 01:34:09,657
I'll tell you one thing that's for certain.

942
01:34:09,821 --> 01:34:13,617
You won't mind dying
once you've peeked over the other side.

943
01:34:17,244 --> 01:34:20,147
You'll no more wanna go back
to your body than...

944
01:34:20,316 --> 01:34:22,684
...you'd wanna spoon up your own puke.

945
01:34:28,922 --> 01:34:31,607
Hey, since we're looking to rob banks...

946
01:34:31,771 --> 01:34:36,179
...I was wondering if we could
add another fella to the gang...

947
01:34:36,346 --> 01:34:39,827
...and sort of see if we couldn't
come out of our next job alive.

948
01:34:42,203 --> 01:34:46,991
Bob wanted to know could he ride with us
next time we took on a savings bank or...

949
01:34:53,050 --> 01:34:55,416
A savings bank or a...

950
01:34:57,081 --> 01:34:58,738
A railroad.

951
01:35:05,817 --> 01:35:08,979
Bob isn't much more than a boy
to most appearances.

952
01:35:09,143 --> 01:35:11,793
But there's about two tons
of sand in him.

953
01:35:11,959 --> 01:35:15,059
And he'll stand with a shooter
when that's what's called for.

954
01:35:15,224 --> 01:35:19,314
And he's smart too.
He's about as intricate as they come.

955
01:35:21,335 --> 01:35:23,954
You forget I already met the kid.

956
01:35:25,205 --> 01:35:27,823
Hell, he surely thinks highly of you.

957
01:35:28,342 --> 01:35:30,992
All of America thinks highly of me.

958
01:35:31,668 --> 01:35:34,769
Still, not like you got two million names
to snatch out of a sock...

959
01:35:34,933 --> 01:35:37,005
...whenever you need a third man.

960
01:35:40,372 --> 01:35:43,274
I can see you trying to
wear me down on this.

961
01:35:43,444 --> 01:35:45,549
That's my main intention.

962
01:35:54,259 --> 01:35:56,813
Robberies would be conceived
but never carried out...

963
01:35:56,978 --> 01:36:00,392
...in Nebraska, Colorado and Missouri.

964
01:36:01,012 --> 01:36:02,060
During this time...

965
01:36:02,228 --> 01:36:06,089
...Henry Craig enjoined Robert Ford to return
to Elias' Grocery Store in Richmond...

966
01:36:06,259 --> 01:36:09,192
...and await instructions
from Sheriff James Timberlake.

967
01:36:09,615 --> 01:36:11,788
All right, three cans...

968
01:36:11,954 --> 01:36:15,532
...peaches. Two cans...

969
01:36:16,754 --> 01:36:19,176
Two cans sifted peas.

970
01:36:19,473 --> 01:36:21,033
One bottle...

971
01:36:23,727 --> 01:36:26,793
...Mary's Morning Tonic, and a half...

972
01:36:29,744 --> 01:36:32,199
Half a sack of flour.

973
01:36:33,329 --> 01:36:35,302
I'll be right with you.

974
01:36:50,636 --> 01:36:52,874
I haven't seen any sign of him.

975
01:36:54,285 --> 01:36:56,555
Well, do you know where he's living?

976
01:36:57,615 --> 01:36:58,923
No.

977
01:37:00,046 --> 01:37:01,419
No?

978
01:37:04,044 --> 01:37:06,695
Well, I can't guess how he does it...

979
01:37:06,860 --> 01:37:10,984
...but he is always knowledgeable
about what's going on.

980
01:37:11,147 --> 01:37:15,272
He's gonna know I've been here with you.
You ought to take that for granted.

981
01:37:17,676 --> 01:37:21,473
And he will kill you if he gets the chance.

982
01:37:24,585 --> 01:37:27,041
Are you willing to risk that?

983
01:37:31,466 --> 01:37:33,124
Yes, I am.

984
01:37:36,073 --> 01:37:37,733
I've been a nobody all my life.

985
01:37:38,635 --> 01:37:40,389
I was the baby.

986
01:37:40,649 --> 01:37:43,944
I was the one they made promises to
that they never kept.

987
01:37:45,095 --> 01:37:49,602
And ever since I can remember it,
Jesse James has been as big as a tree.

988
01:37:52,903 --> 01:37:55,074
I'm prepared for this, Jim...

989
01:37:55,946 --> 01:37:58,017
...and I'm gonna accomplish it.

990
01:37:58,248 --> 01:38:00,255
I know I won't get
but this one opportunity...

991
01:38:00,423 --> 01:38:03,204
...and you can bet your life
I'm not gonna spoil it.

992
01:38:14,726 --> 01:38:15,740
Well...

993
01:38:16,901 --> 01:38:18,812
...wait for your chance.

994
01:38:19,301 --> 01:38:22,563
Don't let yourself be found alone with him,
and do not...

995
01:38:23,397 --> 01:38:25,699
...let him get behind you.

996
01:38:52,676 --> 01:38:53,820
You been chosen.

997
01:38:58,594 --> 01:39:00,120
Well, what do you mean?

998
01:39:01,346 --> 01:39:03,734
Well, your brother said that
you might wanna join us.

999
01:39:03,906 --> 01:39:07,103
But maybe you like this grocery store
more than you said you did.

1000
01:39:10,273 --> 01:39:12,247
- So you missed me?
- Oh, yeah.

1001
01:39:12,896 --> 01:39:15,451
I been crying myself to sleep every night.

1002
01:39:24,608 --> 01:39:26,516
Don't let him see us so much as wink.

1003
01:39:26,687 --> 01:39:30,364
He's suspicious as a damn coyote,
and he don't trust you one iota.

1004
01:39:31,038 --> 01:39:32,762
- Well, I guess that makes...
- Hey.

1005
01:39:32,928 --> 01:39:37,205
He already put away Ed Miller. He said so
like it was something piddly he'd done.

1006
01:40:16,506 --> 01:40:20,566
If we're ever alone for more than a minute,
I'd like a chance to talk to you further.

1007
01:40:58,678 --> 01:41:00,819
They gave me ten days.

1008
01:41:04,533 --> 01:41:05,996
For what?

1009
01:41:07,893 --> 01:41:09,684
For arresting him.

1010
01:41:15,510 --> 01:41:17,103
You and me, huh?

1011
01:41:20,596 --> 01:41:23,728
It's gonna happen one way or another,
Charley. It's gonna happen.

1012
01:41:23,892 --> 01:41:26,380
So it might as well be us
who get rich on it.

1013
01:41:26,547 --> 01:41:29,712
- Bob, he's our friend.
- He murdered Ed Miller.

1014
01:41:30,324 --> 01:41:33,289
And he's gonna murder Liddil and Cummins
if the chance ever comes.

1015
01:41:34,675 --> 01:41:39,115
It seems to me Jesse's riding from
man to man, saying goodbye to the gang.

1016
01:41:40,564 --> 01:41:42,831
So your friendship could put you
under the pansies.

1017
01:41:44,819 --> 01:41:49,093
I'll grind it fine in my mind, Bob. I can't
go any further than that right now.

1018
01:41:52,531 --> 01:41:53,904
You'll come around.

1019
01:41:54,994 --> 01:41:57,360
You think it's all made up, don't you?

1020
01:41:57,522 --> 01:42:00,717
You think it's all yarns
and newspaper stories.

1021
01:42:08,273 --> 01:42:10,509
He's just a human being.

1022
01:42:18,414 --> 01:42:21,414
From now on, you two
won't go anywhere without me.

1023
01:42:22,158 --> 01:42:26,533
From now on, you'll ask for my permission!
From now on, you'll ask to be excused!

1024
01:43:20,170 --> 01:43:24,294
Charley, take them horses
around the barn. Bob, you go on inside.

1025
01:43:25,098 --> 01:43:26,374
- Hello, Mary.
- Hi.

1026
01:43:26,537 --> 01:43:29,570
Look at this rotten parsnip
I found in the compost heap.

1027
01:43:39,368 --> 01:43:41,190
You never mentioned Bob would be here.

1028
01:43:45,286 --> 01:43:48,156
Maybe he was saving it
as a pleasant surprise.

1029
01:43:52,583 --> 01:43:55,135
Got two cousins for company now.

1030
01:44:04,455 --> 01:44:06,657
How it's gonna be is...

1031
01:44:07,013 --> 01:44:11,040
...we'll leave next Monday afternoon
and ride down to Platte City.

1032
01:44:13,798 --> 01:44:15,651
How far is that from Kansas City?

1033
01:44:17,285 --> 01:44:20,001
Platte City's 30 miles south.

1034
01:44:21,573 --> 01:44:25,980
You and me and Charley'll
sleep in the woods overnight...

1035
01:44:26,468 --> 01:44:30,690
...and we'll strike the Wells Bank
sometime before the court recesses.

1036
01:44:35,300 --> 01:44:38,113
What time will that be exactly?

1037
01:44:43,520 --> 01:44:45,943
Well, you don't need to know that.

1038
01:45:00,351 --> 01:45:03,200
You know, I'm real comfortable
with your brother.

1039
01:45:03,424 --> 01:45:05,843
Hell, he's ugly as sin,
he smells like a skunk...

1040
01:45:06,622 --> 01:45:09,918
...and he's so ignorant
he couldn't drive nails in the snow...

1041
01:45:10,079 --> 01:45:12,468
...but he's sort of easy to be around.

1042
01:45:12,958 --> 01:45:15,642
I can't say the same for you, Bob.

1043
01:45:18,910 --> 01:45:21,180
Well, I'm sorry to hear you say that.

1044
01:45:22,974 --> 01:45:26,835
You know how it is when you're
with your girlfriend and the moon's out...

1045
01:45:27,005 --> 01:45:30,900
...and you know she wants to be kissed,
even though she never said so?

1046
01:45:34,171 --> 01:45:35,547
Yeah.

1047
01:45:38,173 --> 01:45:41,402
Well, you're giving me signs
that grieve my soul...

1048
01:45:42,236 --> 01:45:44,276
...and make me wonder...

1049
01:45:44,668 --> 01:45:46,937
...maybe your mind's
been changed about me.

1050
01:45:47,260 --> 01:45:50,575
Well, what do you want me to do?
Swear my good faith on the Bible?

1051
01:46:07,355 --> 01:46:09,208
You two having a spat?

1052
01:46:14,264 --> 01:46:16,654
I was getting ready to be angry.

1053
01:46:21,913 --> 01:46:24,148
Sit over here closer, kid.

1054
01:46:26,297 --> 01:46:27,506
Come on.

1055
01:46:38,198 --> 01:46:40,435
Charley, you'll stay with the animals.

1056
01:46:41,077 --> 01:46:42,900
Me and the kid...

1057
01:46:43,063 --> 01:46:46,858
...will walk into that bank
just before noon.

1058
01:46:48,662 --> 01:46:51,181
Bob will move that cashier...

1059
01:46:51,702 --> 01:46:54,800
...away from the shotgun
that's under the counter...

1060
01:46:54,966 --> 01:46:57,716
...and I'll creep up behind that cashier...

1061
01:46:57,876 --> 01:47:00,113
...and I'll cock his head back like so.

1062
01:47:00,372 --> 01:47:01,354
And I'll say:

1063
01:47:01,524 --> 01:47:04,143
"How come an off-scouring
like you is still sucking air...

1064
01:47:04,308 --> 01:47:06,480
...when so many of mine
are in coffins?" I'll say:

1065
01:47:06,645 --> 01:47:09,839
"How did you get to reach 20
without leaking out all over your clothes?"

1066
01:47:10,290 --> 01:47:14,001
And if I don't like his attitude,
I will slit that phildoodle so deep...

1067
01:47:14,291 --> 01:47:17,194
...he will flop on the floor like a fish.

1068
01:47:20,723 --> 01:47:22,991
My God, what just happened?

1069
01:47:31,857 --> 01:47:35,086
Boy, I could hear your gears grinding...

1070
01:47:35,379 --> 01:47:38,606
...hear your little motor wondering,
"My gosh, what's next?

1071
01:47:38,770 --> 01:47:40,079
What's happening to me?"

1072
01:47:41,873 --> 01:47:43,661
You were precious to behold, Bob.

1073
01:47:43,824 --> 01:47:46,343
You were white as spit in a cotton field.

1074
01:47:46,863 --> 01:47:49,231
You got him. You got him.

1075
01:47:50,799 --> 01:47:54,693
You wanna know how that feels?
Unpleasant. I honestly can't recommend it.

1076
01:47:59,983 --> 01:48:02,351
The old Charley looked stricken!

1077
01:48:02,991 --> 01:48:04,747
I was. I was.

1078
01:48:04,910 --> 01:48:09,698
"This is plumb unexpected," old Charley
was thinking. "That done ruined my day."

1079
01:48:17,165 --> 01:48:18,540
Hell. Hell.

1080
01:48:48,235 --> 01:48:51,944
Jesse slept with Bob
in the children's room that night.

1081
01:48:53,193 --> 01:48:55,680
And Bob remained awake.

1082
01:48:58,409 --> 01:49:01,638
He could see that there was a gun
on the nightstand.

1083
01:49:02,474 --> 01:49:06,302
He could imagine its cold nickel
inside his grip...

1084
01:49:07,178 --> 01:49:10,525
...its two-pound weight
reached out and aimed.

1085
01:49:40,389 --> 01:49:42,395
I need to go to the privy.

1086
01:49:43,558 --> 01:49:46,820
You think you do, but you don't.

1087
01:50:09,090 --> 01:50:11,164
You wait for grace, now.

1088
01:50:12,066 --> 01:50:15,263
- Thank you, Mama.
- Thank you, Zee. God, that looks good.

1089
01:50:15,428 --> 01:50:16,987
- Thank you, Zee.
- You're welcome.

1090
01:50:17,153 --> 01:50:20,121
Well, is this fit to eat or will it just do?

1091
01:50:22,915 --> 01:50:24,921
Woman's cooking's
always been a scandal.

1092
01:50:25,089 --> 01:50:27,358
Cut her meat and the whole table moves.

1093
01:50:28,258 --> 01:50:30,232
You want a biscuit?
You gonna have a biscuit?

1094
01:50:30,401 --> 01:50:34,044
Here's some butter.
Come on. Come on.

1095
01:50:35,904 --> 01:50:37,148
Oh, shoot.

1096
01:50:37,313 --> 01:50:40,957
And so it went,
Jesse was increasingly cavalier...

1097
01:50:41,120 --> 01:50:44,696
...merry, moody, fey...

1098
01:50:44,863 --> 01:50:46,869
...unpredictable.

1099
01:50:48,351 --> 01:50:51,350
He camouflaged his depressions
and derangements...

1100
01:50:51,519 --> 01:50:55,347
...with masquerades
of extreme cordiality, courtesy...

1101
01:50:55,518 --> 01:50:58,168
...and goodwill towards others.

1102
01:50:59,198 --> 01:51:03,289
But even as he jested,
or tickled his boy in the ribs...

1103
01:51:03,454 --> 01:51:06,934
...Jesse would look over at Bob
with melancholy eyes...

1104
01:51:07,102 --> 01:51:10,898
...as if the two were meshed
in an intimate communication.

1105
01:51:13,594 --> 01:51:16,116
Bob was certain that the man
had unriddled him...

1106
01:51:16,284 --> 01:51:18,836
...had seen through his reasons
for coming along...

1107
01:51:19,003 --> 01:51:22,833
...that Jesse could forecast each of
Bob's possible moves and inclinations...

1108
01:51:23,004 --> 01:51:24,761
...and was only acting the innocent...

1109
01:51:24,924 --> 01:51:29,659
...in order to lull Bob
into stupid tranquility and miscalculation.

1110
01:51:50,458 --> 01:51:52,563
How long you been studying me?

1111
01:51:54,394 --> 01:51:57,009
You're gonna break a lot of hearts.

1112
01:52:04,599 --> 01:52:05,745
How do you mean?

1113
01:52:14,615 --> 01:52:16,274
It's a present.

1114
01:52:20,758 --> 01:52:22,252
It's heavy.

1115
01:52:22,806 --> 01:52:24,846
Well, you gonna look inside?

1116
01:52:26,357 --> 01:52:28,081
It's April Fools' Day, you know.

1117
01:52:28,630 --> 01:52:30,386
It ain't no joke.

1118
01:52:37,591 --> 01:52:39,084
Oh, such extravagance.

1119
01:52:40,563 --> 01:52:43,150
Don't that nickel just shine, though?

1120
01:52:43,349 --> 01:52:44,841
It's more than I could hope for.

1121
01:52:45,011 --> 01:52:47,695
I figured that granddaddy Colt
may blow into fragments...

1122
01:52:47,861 --> 01:52:50,510
...next time you try
to squeeze the trigger.

1123
01:52:50,740 --> 01:52:53,041
Well, you might have something there.

1124
01:52:53,523 --> 01:52:56,044
Tom, supper's ready.

1125
01:52:57,171 --> 01:52:59,112
I'll be right there, sweetheart.

1126
01:52:59,282 --> 01:53:01,487
I might be too excited to eat.

1127
01:53:04,627 --> 01:53:07,013
You know what John Newman Edwards
once wrote about me?

1128
01:53:08,018 --> 01:53:10,735
He said I didn't trust
two men in 10,000...

1129
01:53:10,898 --> 01:53:13,450
...and even them I was cautious around.

1130
01:53:14,226 --> 01:53:16,134
Government's sort of run me ragged.

1131
01:53:18,033 --> 01:53:20,902
I'm going the long way around the barn
to say that...

1132
01:53:21,073 --> 01:53:24,552
...I been feeling cornered
and just plain ornery as of late...

1133
01:53:25,263 --> 01:53:29,736
...and I'd be pleased if you'd accept
that gun as my way of apologizing.

1134
01:53:32,016 --> 01:53:34,700
Heaven knows I'd be ornerier
if I were in your position.

1135
01:53:34,864 --> 01:53:37,831
No. No, I haven't been acting correctly.

1136
01:53:39,567 --> 01:53:42,949
Seems I hardly recognize myself
when I'm greased.

1137
01:53:45,902 --> 01:53:48,292
I go on journeys out of my body...

1138
01:53:48,463 --> 01:53:52,390
...and look at my red hands
and my mean face...

1139
01:53:53,134 --> 01:53:56,713
...and I wonder about that man
that's gone so wrong.

1140
01:54:00,334 --> 01:54:03,234
I've been becoming a problem to myself.

1141
01:54:15,371 --> 01:54:16,680
Well...

1142
01:54:23,052 --> 01:54:27,492
- I better wash my hands if supper's on.
- Yeah, go ahead.

1143
01:54:40,298 --> 01:54:43,113
The day before he died was Palm Sunday.

1144
01:54:44,105 --> 01:54:47,268
And Mr. And Mrs. Thomas Howard,
their two children...

1145
01:54:47,432 --> 01:54:49,406
...and their cousin Charles Johnson...

1146
01:54:49,575 --> 01:54:54,530
...strolled to the Second Presbyterian
Church to attend the 10:00 service.

1147
01:54:56,841 --> 01:54:59,043
Bob remained at the cottage...

1148
01:54:59,206 --> 01:55:02,469
...and slyly migrated from room to room.

1149
01:55:04,967 --> 01:55:06,724
He walked into the master bedroom...

1150
01:55:06,887 --> 01:55:10,499
...and inventoried the clothes
on the hangers and hooks.

1151
01:55:16,550 --> 01:55:19,746
He sipped from the water glass
on the vanity.

1152
01:55:21,989 --> 01:55:26,081
He smelled the talcum and lilacs
on Jesse's pillowcase.

1153
01:55:33,668 --> 01:55:35,773
His fingers skittered over his ribs...

1154
01:55:35,940 --> 01:55:39,649
...to construe the scars
where Jesse was twice shot.

1155
01:55:43,299 --> 01:55:47,707
He manufactured a middle finger
that was missing the top two knuckles.

1156
01:55:54,850 --> 01:55:57,664
He imagined himself at 34.

1157
01:55:59,586 --> 01:56:02,456
He imagined himself in a coffin.

1158
01:56:04,450 --> 01:56:06,107
He considered possibilities...

1159
01:56:06,273 --> 01:56:09,437
...and everything wonderful
that could come true.

1160
01:56:36,095 --> 01:56:37,947
He's not gonna kill us.

1161
01:56:42,973 --> 01:56:45,047
Yeah, he is.

1162
01:56:47,261 --> 01:56:49,651
Well, I'll stay awake so he can't.

1163
01:57:02,459 --> 01:57:04,794
You're imagining things.

1164
01:57:16,538 --> 01:57:18,428
Ain't gonna be no Platte City.

1165
01:57:20,090 --> 01:57:22,609
That's Jesse fooling with us.

1166
01:57:38,360 --> 01:57:40,500
Go to sleep, Charley.

1167
01:58:12,726 --> 01:58:14,252
Morning.

1168
01:58:17,909 --> 01:58:19,371
Charley.

1169
01:58:47,986 --> 01:58:50,319
Bob, how much did you want to eat?

1170
01:58:54,642 --> 01:58:56,976
I'm feeling sort of peculiar.

1171
01:59:15,406 --> 01:59:17,774
Why is it you're looking so interested?

1172
01:59:19,183 --> 01:59:21,966
You think it's intelligent
to go out like that...

1173
01:59:22,127 --> 01:59:23,883
...so all creation can see your guns?

1174
01:59:40,910 --> 01:59:42,282
Hi.

1175
01:59:52,172 --> 01:59:54,954
Come on, let's go see
what your mama's doing.

1176
01:59:56,043 --> 01:59:58,083
Timmy, get that door, would you?

1177
02:00:02,058 --> 02:00:05,093
- Well, you lost your shoe, sweetheart.
- Yeah, I did.

1178
02:00:05,260 --> 02:00:09,219
That's gonna be a problem.
They don't sell those one at a time.

1179
02:00:10,666 --> 02:00:12,639
We lost a shoe, Mama.

1180
02:00:14,186 --> 02:00:16,642
Will you put that up for Daddy,
would you?

1181
02:00:19,595 --> 02:00:22,244
- What you doing, you lose a shoe?
- Yeah.

1182
02:00:38,279 --> 02:00:41,541
It's only meant to go on top,
to complement.

1183
02:00:41,799 --> 02:00:43,554
Yeah, I know. Sometimes, l...

1184
02:01:07,140 --> 02:01:09,921
Bob, everything's getting cold!

1185
02:01:10,595 --> 02:01:13,857
- Where's Mary?
- She's outside, darling.

1186
02:01:14,819 --> 02:01:16,544
Mary?

1187
02:01:20,164 --> 02:01:22,584
What do you think goes on
in that noggin of his?

1188
02:01:25,476 --> 02:01:27,101
Nothing.

1189
02:01:27,650 --> 02:01:30,335
I was talking about his mind, not yours.

1190
02:01:31,234 --> 02:01:32,893
Oh, yeah.

1191
02:01:33,314 --> 02:01:34,941
Oh, I get it.

1192
02:02:28,093 --> 02:02:29,982
Well, hello now.

1193
02:02:30,367 --> 02:02:33,267
"The arrest and confession
of Dick Liddil."

1194
02:02:38,300 --> 02:02:40,374
You don't say so.

1195
02:02:54,107 --> 02:02:56,113
That's very strange.

1196
02:02:56,539 --> 02:02:59,321
Says here Dick surrendered
three weeks ago.

1197
02:02:59,483 --> 02:03:01,969
You must have been
right in the neighborhood.

1198
02:03:02,618 --> 02:03:05,138
Well, apparently, they kept it a secret.

1199
02:03:15,896 --> 02:03:18,830
If I get to Kansas City soon,
I'll ask somebody about it.

1200
02:03:57,844 --> 02:03:59,470
You two ready?

1201
02:04:03,029 --> 02:04:05,580
I will be, by noon.

1202
02:04:37,136 --> 02:04:39,689
There is a ship
She sails the sea

1203
02:04:39,856 --> 02:04:42,507
She's loaded deep
As deep can be

1204
02:04:42,674 --> 02:04:44,811
But not as deep
As the love I'm in

1205
02:04:45,360 --> 02:04:48,842
I know not if I sink or swim

1206
02:04:49,840 --> 02:04:51,466
The water is wide

1207
02:04:52,560 --> 02:04:58,853
I can't cross o'er
And neither have I wings to fly

1208
02:04:59,278 --> 02:05:02,923
Give me a boat
That can carry two

1209
02:05:03,088 --> 02:05:05,838
Both shall row
My love and I

1210
02:05:06,000 --> 02:05:09,315
For love is gentle
And love is kind

1211
02:05:09,486 --> 02:05:12,356
Sweetest flower
When first it's new

1212
02:05:12,527 --> 02:05:15,973
But love grows old
And waxes cold

1213
02:05:16,140 --> 02:05:19,239
And fades away
Like the morning dew

1214
02:05:19,406 --> 02:05:22,306
There is a ship
She sails the sea

1215
02:05:22,476 --> 02:05:25,128
I guess I'll take my guns off...

1216
02:05:25,451 --> 02:05:27,361
...for fear the neighbors might spy them.

1217
02:05:59,305 --> 02:06:01,641
Don't that picture look dusty?

1218
02:07:39,552 --> 02:07:42,423
What have...? What have you done?

1219
02:07:44,767 --> 02:07:46,329
Jesse.

1220
02:07:51,646 --> 02:07:52,629
Jesse?

1221
02:07:53,727 --> 02:07:55,768
Jesse? Jesse?

1222
02:07:56,481 --> 02:07:58,267
Jesse!

1223
02:07:59,231 --> 02:08:01,237
No!

1224
02:08:05,245 --> 02:08:07,482
No. Jess...

1225
02:08:08,062 --> 02:08:12,283
Come back. Oh, come back.

1226
02:08:14,332 --> 02:08:18,326
Oh, Jesse! No!

1227
02:08:18,813 --> 02:08:22,555
Oh, Bob. Have you done this?!

1228
02:08:22,749 --> 02:08:25,016
I swear to God I didn't.

1229
02:08:25,978 --> 02:08:27,353
It was an accident, Zee.

1230
02:08:29,467 --> 02:08:32,696
Come on. Pistol went off accidentally.

1231
02:09:16,182 --> 02:09:17,326
Put my name.

1232
02:09:17,494 --> 02:09:19,862
Why, what'd you do? I shot him.

1233
02:09:26,774 --> 02:09:28,717
You might wanna keep that.

1234
02:10:05,106 --> 02:10:07,113
Thank you all very much.

1235
02:10:14,929 --> 02:10:17,317
The resulting prints
sold for 2 dollars apiece...

1236
02:10:17,489 --> 02:10:21,895
...and were the models for the lithographed
covers on a number of magazines.

1237
02:10:27,217 --> 02:10:32,201
Soon a thousand strangers were making
spellbound pilgrimages to the cottage...

1238
02:10:32,559 --> 02:10:36,902
...or were venerating the iced remains
in Seidenfaden's cooling room.

1239
02:10:37,776 --> 02:10:42,085
The man who offered 30,000 dollars for
the body of President Garfield's assassin...

1240
02:10:42,254 --> 02:10:45,997
...sent a telegram to City Marshal
Enos Craig offering 50,000...

1241
02:10:46,160 --> 02:10:48,362
...for the body
of Jesse Woodson James...

1242
02:10:48,524 --> 02:10:51,177
...so that he could go around the country
with it...

1243
02:10:53,484 --> 02:10:58,242
...or at least sell it to P.T. Barnum
for his Greatest Show on Earth.

1244
02:11:02,157 --> 02:11:05,124
Another photograph was taken
of the renowned American bandit...

1245
02:11:05,292 --> 02:11:07,778
...nestled in his bed of ice.

1246
02:11:07,948 --> 02:11:12,039
And it was this shot that was most
available in sundries and apothecaries...

1247
02:11:12,204 --> 02:11:15,716
...to be viewed in a stereoscope
alongside the sphinx...

1248
02:11:15,883 --> 02:11:19,712
...the Taj Mahal,
and the catacombs of Rome.

1249
02:11:43,881 --> 02:11:45,768
Hello, here!

1250
02:11:45,961 --> 02:11:48,449
"The arrest and confession
of Dick Liddil."

1251
02:11:48,616 --> 02:11:53,538
Young man, I thought you told me
you didn't know Dick had surrendered.

1252
02:11:53,704 --> 02:11:57,412
You mean he did? I didn't know.

1253
02:11:58,279 --> 02:12:00,101
But I knew I had not fooled him.

1254
02:12:00,263 --> 02:12:03,940
And he knew, as well as I, in that moment
that I intended to bring him to justice.

1255
02:12:04,840 --> 02:12:08,256
But he would not kill me
in the presence of his wife and children.

1256
02:12:08,422 --> 02:12:11,521
And so he was smiling
to throw me off-guard.

1257
02:12:14,629 --> 02:12:17,182
Well, it's all right, anyway, Bob.

1258
02:12:18,982 --> 02:12:21,764
It was widely felt that
Bob possessed some acting talent...

1259
02:12:21,925 --> 02:12:24,097
...and Charley, not a jot.

1260
02:12:24,261 --> 02:12:27,076
That picture's awful dusty.

1261
02:12:27,845 --> 02:12:30,845
Charley was only expected
not to slouch or mutter...

1262
02:12:31,014 --> 02:12:35,485
...and to transport his sicknesses
to the alley before letting them go.

1263
02:13:03,681 --> 02:13:05,470
And that's...

1264
02:13:06,017 --> 02:13:08,569
...how I killed Jesse James.

1265
02:13:11,905 --> 02:13:15,288
By October of 1883, Bob Ford
could be identified correctly...

1266
02:13:15,457 --> 02:13:19,548
...by more citizens than could
the president of the United States.

1267
02:13:20,192 --> 02:13:24,730
He was as renowned at 20 as Jesse was
after 14 years of grand larceny.

1268
02:13:24,894 --> 02:13:27,000
You won't get your hooks into me.

1269
02:13:27,519 --> 02:13:32,058
That's right. That's right.
Sit next to your boyfriend. Jezebel.

1270
02:13:32,222 --> 02:13:34,230
Charley was increasingly superstitious...

1271
02:13:34,399 --> 02:13:36,983
...increasingly subject
to the advice of soothsayers...

1272
02:13:37,151 --> 02:13:41,013
...who promised to cure his miseries
with pipe smoke and poultices.

1273
02:13:41,181 --> 02:13:44,313
You been spending too much time
with Gypsies, Charley.

1274
02:13:49,790 --> 02:13:51,098
Shit.

1275
02:13:55,260 --> 02:13:57,714
The picture's awful dusty.

1276
02:13:58,140 --> 02:14:01,817
Something began to change
in Charley's stage portrayal of Jesse.

1277
02:14:01,980 --> 02:14:04,404
His gait seemed more practiced.

1278
02:14:04,573 --> 02:14:07,735
His voice was spookily similar
to the man's.

1279
02:14:07,901 --> 02:14:10,200
His newly suggested dialogue
was analogous...

1280
02:14:10,363 --> 02:14:13,265
...to a script Jesse might have originated.

1281
02:14:15,962 --> 02:14:18,297
He began to look at his younger brother
with spite...

1282
02:14:18,460 --> 02:14:20,978
...as if he suspected that
in some future performance...

1283
02:14:21,147 --> 02:14:25,489
...he might present himself
to a live cartridge in Robert Ford's gun.

1284
02:14:26,778 --> 02:14:28,534
Murderer!

1285
02:14:28,857 --> 02:14:30,516
Cur!

1286
02:14:31,130 --> 02:14:32,819
Coward!

1287
02:14:36,217 --> 02:14:40,558
You wanna investigate my courage?
Do you?

1288
02:14:40,953 --> 02:14:44,565
Find out! Find out!

1289
02:14:49,016 --> 02:14:50,804
Nobody.

1290
02:15:04,789 --> 02:15:06,514
Coward!

1291
02:15:30,675 --> 02:15:36,012
By his own approximation, Bob
assassinated Jesse James over 800 times.

1292
02:15:36,180 --> 02:15:39,790
He suspected no one in history
had ever so often or so publicly...

1293
02:15:39,954 --> 02:15:43,019
...recapitulated an act of betrayal.

1294
02:15:48,017 --> 02:15:50,668
Bob always challenged
the allegations of cowardice...

1295
02:15:50,833 --> 02:15:53,650
...but Charley seemed
to agree with them.

1296
02:15:53,907 --> 02:15:57,518
He spoke of Mrs. Zee James
as certain priests might the Madonna...

1297
02:15:57,682 --> 02:16:00,647
...and composed long soul-describing letters
to her...

1298
02:16:00,817 --> 02:16:02,921
...begging her forgiveness...

1299
02:16:04,176 --> 02:16:06,665
...none of which he mailed.

1300
02:16:33,390 --> 02:16:38,756
Charley Ford became all that his countrymen
wanted an assassin of Jesse James to be.

1301
02:16:42,860 --> 02:16:48,490
Jesse James was a man
Who killed many men

1302
02:16:49,643 --> 02:16:53,900
He robbed the Glendale train

1303
02:16:54,125 --> 02:16:59,720
And he stole from the rich
And he gave to the poor

1304
02:16:59,948 --> 02:17:04,683
He had a hand
And a heart and a brain

1305
02:17:05,452 --> 02:17:10,719
Well, Jesse had a wife
To mourn for his life

1306
02:17:10,890 --> 02:17:15,777
Three children
They were brave

1307
02:17:15,945 --> 02:17:21,314
But that dirty little coward
Who shot Mr. Howard

1308
02:17:21,545 --> 02:17:26,401
Has laid Jesse James in his grave

1309
02:17:27,432 --> 02:17:32,223
It was Robert Ford
That dirty little coward

1310
02:17:32,937 --> 02:17:37,157
I wonder how does he feel

1311
02:17:37,318 --> 02:17:42,817
For he ate at Jesse's bread
And he slept in Jesse's bed

1312
02:17:42,982 --> 02:17:47,807
And he laid poor Jesse in his grave

1313
02:17:48,263 --> 02:17:53,566
Well, Jesse had a wife
To mourn for his life

1314
02:17:53,734 --> 02:17:58,436
Three children
They were brave

1315
02:17:58,597 --> 02:18:03,998
But that dirty little coward
Who shot Mr. Howard

1316
02:18:04,166 --> 02:18:08,158
Has laid poor Jesse in his grave

1317
02:18:19,237 --> 02:18:21,176
I'm Robert Ford.

1318
02:18:31,460 --> 02:18:35,035
It was two children, not three.

1319
02:18:45,953 --> 02:18:47,230
Hey.

1320
02:18:48,096 --> 02:18:50,551
You get yourself home, son, okay?

1321
02:18:51,232 --> 02:18:55,095
Come on. Get out of here.
Get out of my place.

1322
02:19:25,566 --> 02:19:27,669
He thought, at his angriest...

1323
02:19:27,836 --> 02:19:31,447
...about visiting the kin
of Jesse's slaughtered victims:

1324
02:19:33,339 --> 02:19:36,470
Mrs. William Westfall in Plattsburg...

1325
02:19:38,878 --> 02:19:41,843
...the Wymore family in Clay County...

1326
02:19:46,778 --> 02:19:50,903
...perhaps even Mrs. Joseph Heywood
in Northfield, Minnesota.

1327
02:19:53,849 --> 02:19:56,719
He would go to their homes
and give his name as Robert Ford...

1328
02:19:56,890 --> 02:19:59,736
...the man who killed Jesse James.

1329
02:20:01,114 --> 02:20:04,049
He imagined they would
be grateful to him.

1330
02:20:52,917 --> 02:20:57,706
It was only with Dorothy Evans
that Bob spoke revealingly or plainly...

1331
02:20:57,878 --> 02:21:02,131
...and it was with her that he spoke of
things he didn't know he knew.

1332
02:21:22,900 --> 02:21:26,793
He told her that he had no real memory
of the shooting and its aftermath.

1333
02:21:26,961 --> 02:21:30,671
He could remember lifting the gun
that Jesse had given him...

1334
02:21:31,378 --> 02:21:35,239
...and then it was Good Friday and he was
reading about the funeral proceedings...

1335
02:21:35,409 --> 02:21:37,830
...as if they'd happened a long time ago.

1336
02:21:39,343 --> 02:21:41,384
Why did you kill him?

1337
02:21:45,521 --> 02:21:47,463
Well, he was gonna kill me.

1338
02:21:52,463 --> 02:21:55,561
So you were scared
and that's the only reason?

1339
02:21:58,191 --> 02:21:59,532
Yeah.

1340
02:21:59,982 --> 02:22:01,958
And the reward money.

1341
02:22:07,534 --> 02:22:10,217
Do you want me to change the subject?

1342
02:22:18,093 --> 02:22:20,328
You know what I expected?

1343
02:22:21,324 --> 02:22:23,233
Applause.

1344
02:22:25,709 --> 02:22:29,703
I was only 20 years old then.
I couldn't see how it would look to people.

1345
02:22:33,645 --> 02:22:36,196
I was surprised by what happened.

1346
02:22:37,229 --> 02:22:39,115
They didn't applaud.

1347
02:22:42,411 --> 02:22:44,199
He was ashamed of his boasting...

1348
02:22:44,362 --> 02:22:47,113
...his pretensions of courage
and ruthlessness.

1349
02:22:47,403 --> 02:22:51,015
He was sorry about his cold-bloodedness,
his dispassion...

1350
02:22:52,586 --> 02:22:56,809
...his inability to express
what he now believed was the case:

1351
02:22:59,273 --> 02:23:02,175
That he truly regretted killing Jesse...

1352
02:23:02,919 --> 02:23:05,790
...that he missed the man
as much as anybody...

1353
02:23:06,312 --> 02:23:09,313
...and wished his murder
hadn't been necessary.

1354
02:23:27,975 --> 02:23:29,982
Even as he circulated his saloon...

1355
02:23:30,152 --> 02:23:33,761
...he knew that the smiles disappeared
when he passed by.

1356
02:23:34,822 --> 02:23:36,579
He received so many menacing letters...

1357
02:23:36,742 --> 02:23:40,037
...that he could read them
without any reaction except curiosity.

1358
02:23:43,686 --> 02:23:48,288
He kept to his apartment all day,
flipping over playing cards...

1359
02:23:49,732 --> 02:23:54,042
...looking at his destiny
in every king and jack.

1360
02:23:58,084 --> 02:24:02,208
Edward O'Kelly came up from Bachelor
at 1 p.m. On the 8th.

1361
02:24:03,619 --> 02:24:07,394
He had no grand scheme, no strategy...

1362
02:24:07,555 --> 02:24:09,858
...no agreement with higher authorities...

1363
02:24:10,019 --> 02:24:12,669
...nothing beyond
a vague longing for glory...

1364
02:24:13,699 --> 02:24:17,788
...and a generalized wish
for revenge against Robert Ford.

1365
02:24:25,251 --> 02:24:28,380
- How'd it go last night?
- Not so bad.

1366
02:24:31,488 --> 02:24:32,830
The other one.

1367
02:24:35,232 --> 02:24:37,882
Edward O'Kelly would be ordered
to serve a life sentence...

1368
02:24:38,048 --> 02:24:40,830
...in the Colorado Penitentiary
for second-degree murder.

1369
02:24:40,994 --> 02:24:43,642
Over 7000 signatures
would eventually be gathered...

1370
02:24:43,807 --> 02:24:45,979
...on a petition asking for
O'Kelly's release...

1371
02:24:46,144 --> 02:24:50,932
...and in 1902, Governor James B. Orman
would pardon the man.

1372
02:24:51,519 --> 02:24:55,741
You shouldn't be wearing that stickpin
again there, Bob. Opals are unlucky.

1373
02:24:57,118 --> 02:25:01,142
My luck's not very good as it is. I don't
think an opal's gonna change that much.

1374
02:25:02,046 --> 02:25:03,420
I hear you.

1375
02:25:16,443 --> 02:25:18,234
There would be no eulogies for Bob...

1376
02:25:19,868 --> 02:25:23,796
...no photographs of his body
would be sold in sundries stores...

1377
02:25:24,475 --> 02:25:28,666
...no people would crowd the streets
in the rain to see his funeral cortege...

1378
02:25:30,331 --> 02:25:33,180
...no biographies would be written
about him...

1379
02:25:33,340 --> 02:25:35,794
...no children named after him.

1380
02:25:37,307 --> 02:25:41,846
No one would ever pay 25 cents
to stand in the rooms he grew up in.

1381
02:25:46,202 --> 02:25:47,860
Hello, Bob.

1382
02:25:49,241 --> 02:25:53,266
The shotgun would ignite,
and Ella Mae would scream...

1383
02:25:54,040 --> 02:25:57,553
...but Robert Ford would only lay
on the floor and look at the ceiling...

1384
02:25:57,720 --> 02:26:00,109
...the light going out of his eyes...

1385
02:26:00,280 --> 02:26:02,897
...before he could find the right words.

1386
02:26:18,614 --> 02:26:28,217
THE END
